-mjx-texclass=3D"INNER"><mo data-mjx-texclass=3D"OPEN">[</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>=
,</mo><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=E2=88=9E</mi><mo data-mjx-texclass=3D"CLO=
SE">)</mo></mrow></math></mjx-assistive-mml></mjx-container>. This is perha=
ps the most useful method, as it applies to concepts studied later in this =
course and to other higher-level math courses.</p>
<p>The main concept to remember is that parentheses represent solutions gre=
ater or less than the number, and brackets represent solutions that are gre=
ater than or equal to or less than or equal to the number. Use parentheses =
to represent infinity or negative infinity, since positive and negative inf=
inity are not numbers in the usual sense of the word and, therefore, cannot=
 be =E2=80=9Cequaled.=E2=80=9D A few examples of an <strong>interval</stron=
g>, or a set of numbers in which a solution falls, are <mjx-container class=
